Believers in Free Trade
From Cambridge — — Recently, I was invited to be a guest lecturer in a globalization course taught by two Harvard colleagues. "I must warn you,"
one of them warned me in advance, "these students are ardent supporters of globalization."
He had them vote on free trade versus import restrictions in the first class, with over 90% opting for the former.
And this was before he even started teaching the magical effect of comparative advantage.
We know that in a real investigation, asking the same questions to representative samples — not Harvard students — would yield a completely different result.
In the United States, the ratio of opponents to supporters of trade restrictions is 2:1.
But the answers of Harvard students are not particularly surprising.
Because those with higher technology and better education tend to be more inclined to support free trade than blue-collar workers.
Perhaps these Harvard students have already expected their own (financial) prospects and made decisions accordingly.
Or maybe they don't really understand how trade works.
After all, when I met them, I deliberately framed the same question in a different way, and emphasized the possible distributive effects of trade.
The consensus in favor of fair trade disappeared completely, and even faster than I thought.
From the beginning, I first asked everyone if they agreed to my conducting a particularly magical experiment.
I chose Nicholas and John as volunteers, then told them that I could make $200 disappear from Nicholas's account – poof! – and at the same time increase John's account by $300, and the social engineering feat could make the class as a whole increase by an additional $100 in value.
So they would allow me to play this little trick?
Only a very small part of them decided to agree, many people were hesitant, and even more people opposed implementing this change.

It's obvious that the students find it hard to accept this form of large-scale income redistribution, even when the economic pie has been enlarged.
I then asked why most of them nearly instinctively supported free trade, while free trade would also lead to a similar — indeed an even greater — wealth redistribution from losers to winners.
Students looked stunned.
I continued, "Let's assume both Nicholas and John had started a small competing company."
John worked harder, invested more, and produced better products, so he not only had $300 more than Nicholas, but also forced him out of the market and caused him to lose $200.
How many students were in favor of this change?
Most of them voted in favor this time — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then proposed another hypothesis directly related to international trade.
Is John driving Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or is it by outsourcing business processes to China, where labor rights are still imperfect?
Or by hiring child labor in Indonesia?
Approval for this transition decreased with each of the above options in turn.
Aside from economic inequality, technological innovation will also lead to some people being in a weaker position, just like trade. What is your stance on this?
Only a small number of students are willing to restrain the development of technology.
For almost everyone, banning the production of light bulbs in order to preserve the jobs of candle makers is a ridiculous idea.
Therefore, students do not necessarily oppose redistribution, but rather oppose certain specific forms of it.
Like most of us, they are concerned with the fairness of the program.
If we are to make a judgment about the re-allocation results, we must know the objective environment that produces such results.
We will not be resentful about Bill Gates or Warren Buffett's enormous wealth, even if some of their rivals have been living a hard life, mostly because they and their competitors are all operating under the same basic rules, facing extremely similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett were not relying on their intelligence and efforts, but instead cheating, violating labor laws, destroying the environment, or using foreign government subsidies to get rich, our thoughts would be completely different.
If we cannot tolerate re-allocation achieved by violating the moral rules widely followed in the country, why can we feel at ease about it just because it involves cross-border transactions?
Similarly, when we expect the re-allocation effects to achieve equality in the long run, and everyone will ultimately benefit from it, we are likely to be indifferent to income transfers.
This is also why we believe that even though technology may bring negative reactions to some people in the short term, we still want to promote its development as the key reason.
On the other hand, when trade continues to hit the same group of people - low-educated blue-collar workers - we will be worried about globalization again.
However, many economists ignore these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute their concerns about globalization to silly and selfish trade protectionism or ignorance, rather than realizing that the most important thing is a moral issue.
Because they cannot realize that international trade may sometimes - of course, not often - lead to some redistributive consequences that we cannot accept at home, these economists also cannot intervene in public discussions appropriately.
However, since they can't stand on their ground morally, how can they fiercely defend trade?
When globalization occasionally triggers a difficult problem related to the legalization of redistribution effect, we should not hastily use trade restrictions as a response.
There are many pros and cons that need to be weighed heavily, including the possible wealth deprivation that globalization may cause to people in other places more severely than to victims in the United States.
Democratic countries should have a more fitting discussion on this and make conscious and more deliberate decisions accordingly.
The practice of being infatuated with globalization solely because it makes the cake bigger will inevitably erode the legitimacy of globalization in the long run.
